'''Kodaishi-yama''' (孔大寺山), also read as '''Kodaishi-san''', is a 499-meter-high mountain located on the border of {{ill|Munakata City|ja|宗像市}} and {{ill|Okagaki Town|ja|岡垣町}} in {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|ja|福岡県}}. It is the highest peak among the {{ill|Four Peaks of Munakata|ja|宗像四塚}}. To the east lies {{ill|Kanayama|ja|金山}}, to the west is {{ill|Yukawadake|ja|湯川山}}, and to the south stretches {{ill|Hakusan|ja|白山 (宗像市)}}.
== Overview == Like the other peaks in the {{ill|Shizuka Mountain Range|ja|四塚連山}}, Kodaishi-yama was formed by the eruption of an ancient {{ill|submarine volcano|ja|海底火山}} approximately 100 million years ago.
According to the ''Munakata District Gazetteer'' (宗像郡誌), the mountain is named "Kodaishi" because of a large hole at its summit. Legend holds that a {{ill|great serpent|ja|大蛇}} (an {{ill|Aragami|ja|荒神}} or fierce deity) once resided in this hole, requiring human sacrifices. However, after {{ill|Saichō|ja|最澄}} (also known as Dengyō Daishi) performed rituals, the malevolent spirit ceased to appear.
At the 8th station of the mountain stands {{ill|Kodaishi Gongen|ja|孔大寺権現}} (a {{ill|sessha|ja|摂社}} of {{ill|Munakata Taisha|ja|宗像大社}}, also known as {{ill|Kodaishi Shrine|ja|孔大寺神社}}). The approach to the shrine begins near the Ikeda intersection at the base, marked by the first {{ill|torii|ja|鳥居}} gate, and consists of 800 stone steps leading to the main shrine. The enshrined deities are {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大己尊命}} and {{ill|Sukunahikona|ja|少名彦命}}.
A notable feature is the giant ginkgo tree, designated as a {{ill|Prefectural Natural Monument|ja|天然記念物}}. This tree stands 34.6 meters tall, with a trunk circumference of 6 meters and a root spread of 9.4 meters, estimated to be around 300 years old.
In 701 CE, the {{ill|ascetic|ja|役行者}} {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役行者}} established the {{ill|Three Peaks Syncretic Path|ja|三部習合之峰}} with {{ill|Mount Hōman|ja|宝満山}} and {{ill|Mount Hikosan|ja|英彦山}}. Kodaishi-yama became one of the three sacred mountains for {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道}} practitioners, where ascetic training rituals were conducted periodically. At the foot of the mountain in the Senga area, ruins of {{ill|yamabushi|ja|山伏}} residences remain, historically referred to as ''Sengakubō'' (仙岳坊).
== Geography == * Located on the border between the former {{ill|Munakata District|ja|宗像郡}} and {{ill|Onga District|ja|遠賀郡}}.
