At the 8th station of the mountain stands {{ill|Kodaishi Gongen|ja|孔大寺権現|qq=draft}} (a {{ill|sessha|ja|摂社|qq=draft}} of {{ill|Munakata Taisha|ja|宗像大社|qq=draft}}, also known as {{ill|Kodaishi Shrine|ja|孔大寺神社|qq=draft}}). The approach to the shrine begins near the Ikeda intersection at the base, marked by the first {{ill|torii|ja|鳥居|qq=draft}} gate, and consists of 800 stone steps leading to the main shrine. The enshrined deities are {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大己尊命|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Sukunahikona|ja|少名彦命|qq=draft}}.
A notable feature is the giant ginkgo tree, designated as a {{ill|Prefectural Natural Monument|ja|天然記念物|qq=draft}}. This tree stands 34.6 meters tall, with a trunk circumference of 6 meters and a root spread of 9.4 meters, estimated to be around 300 years old.
In 701 CE, the {{ill|ascetic|ja|役行者|qq=draft}} {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役行者|qq=draft}} established the {{ill|Three Peaks Syncretic Path|ja|三部習合之峰|qq=draft}} with {{ill|Mount Hōman|ja|宝満山|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Mount Hikosan|ja|英彦山|qq=draft}}. Kodaishi-yama became one of the three sacred mountains for {{ill|Shugendō|ja|修験道|qq=draft}} practitioners, where ascetic training rituals were conducted periodically. At the foot of the mountain in the Senga area, ruins of {{ill|yamabushi|ja|山伏|qq=draft}} residences remain, historically referred to as ''Sengakubō'' (仙岳坊).
== Geography == * Located on the border between the former {{ill|Munakata District|ja|宗像郡|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Onga District|ja|遠賀郡|qq=draft}}.
