At the 8th station of the mountain stands {{ill|Kodaishi Gongen|ja|孔大寺権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kodaishi Gongen|qq=}} (a {{ill|sessha|ja|摂社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/sessha|qq=}} of [[:en:Munakata Taisha|Munakata Taisha]], also known as {{ill|Kodaishi Shrine|ja|孔大寺神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kodaishi Shrine|qq=}}). The approach to the shrine begins near the Ikeda intersection at the base, marked by the first [[:en:Torii|torii]] gate, and consists of 800 stone steps leading to the main shrine. The enshrined deities are {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大己尊命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkuninushi|qq=}} and {{ill|Sukunabikona|lt=Sukunabikona|lt=Sukunahikona|ja|少名彦命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunahikona|qq=}}.
A notable feature is the giant ginkgo tree, designated as a [[:en:Natural monument|Prefectural Natural Monument]]. This tree stands 34.6 meters tall, with a trunk circumference of 6 meters and a root spread of 9.4 meters, estimated to be around 300 years old.
In 701 CE, the {{ill|ascetic|ja|役行者|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ascetic|qq=}} {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役行者|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/En no Gyōja|qq=}} established the {{ill|Three Peaks Syncretic Path|ja|三部習合之峰|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Three Peaks Syncretic Path|qq=}} with [[:en:Mount Hōman|Mount Hōman]] and [[:en:Mount Hiko|Mount Hikosan]]. Kodaishi-yama became one of the three sacred mountains for [[:en:Shugendō|Shugendō]] practitioners, where ascetic training rituals were conducted periodically. At the foot of the mountain in the Senga area, ruins of [[:en:Yamabushi|yamabushi]] residences remain, historically referred to as ''Sengakubō'' (仙岳坊).
