'''Kodaishi-yama''' (孔大寺山), also read as '''Kodaishi-san''', is a 499-meter-high mountain located on the border of [[:en:Munakata, Fukuoka|Munakata City]] and [[:en:Okagaki, Fukuoka|Okagaki Town]] in [[:en:Fukuoka Prefecture|Fukuoka Prefecture]]. It is the highest peak among the {{ill|Four Peaks of Munakata|ja|宗像四塚|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Four Peaks of Munakata|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 四塚連山}}. To the east lies [[:en:金山|Kanayama]], to the west is {{ill|Yukawadake|ja|湯川山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yukawadake|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, and to the south stretches {{ill|Hakusan|ja|白山 (宗像市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakusan|qq=}}.
== Overview == Like the other peaks in the {{ill|Shizuka Mountain Range|ja|四塚連山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shizuka Mountain Range|qq=}}, Kodaishi-yama was formed by the eruption of an ancient [[:en:Submarine volcano|submarine volcano]] approximately 100 million years ago.
According to the ''Munakata District Gazetteer'' (宗像郡誌), the mountain is named "Kodaishi" because of a large hole at its summit. Legend holds that a {{ill|great serpent|ja|大蛇|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/great serpent|qq=}} (an [[:en:Kōjin|Aragami]] or fierce deity) once resided in this hole, requiring human sacrifices. However, after [[:en:Saichō|Saichō]] (also known as Dengyō Daishi) performed rituals, the malevolent spirit ceased to appear.
At the 8th station of the mountain stands {{ill|Kodaishi Gongen|ja|孔大寺権現|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kodaishi Gongen|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (a {{ill|sessha|ja|摂社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/sessha|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 摂末社}} of [[:en:Munakata Taisha|Munakata Taisha]], also known as {{ill|Kodaishi Shrine|ja|孔大寺神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kodaishi Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}). The approach to the shrine begins near the Ikeda intersection at the base, marked by the first [[:en:Torii|torii]] gate, and consists of 800 stone steps leading to the main shrine. The enshrined deities are {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大己尊命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōkuninushi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and {{ill|Sukunabikona|lt=Sukunabikona|lt=Sukunahikona|ja|少名彦命|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sukunahikona|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to スクナビコナ}}.
A notable feature is the giant ginkgo tree, designated as a [[:en:Natural monument|Prefectural Natural Monument]]. This tree stands 34.6 meters tall, with a trunk circumference of 6 meters and a root spread of 9.4 meters, estimated to be around 300 years old.
In 701 CE, the {{ill|ascetic|ja|役行者|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ascetic|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 役小角}} {{ill|En no Gyōja|ja|役行者|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/En no Gyōja|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 役小角}} established the {{ill|Three Peaks Syncretic Path|ja|三部習合之峰|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Three Peaks Syncretic Path|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} with [[:en:Mount Hōman|Mount Hōman]] and [[:en:Mount Hiko|Mount Hikosan]]. Kodaishi-yama became one of the three sacred mountains for [[:en:Shugendō|Shugendō]] practitioners, where ascetic training rituals were conducted periodically. At the foot of the mountain in the Senga area, ruins of [[:en:Yamabushi|yamabushi]] residences remain, historically referred to as ''Sengakubō'' (仙岳坊).
== Geography == * Located on the border between the former [[:en:Munakata District, Fukuoka|Munakata District]] and [[:en:Onga District, Fukuoka|Onga District]].
